  <page>
    <title>Gold code</title>
    <ns>0</ns>
    <id>50567</id>
    <revision>
      <id>935600628</id>
      <parentid>929028498</parentid>
      <timestamp>2020-01-13T15:53:55Z</timestamp>
      <contributor>
        <ip>114.36.81.56</ip>
      </contributor>
      <comment>The set of gold code sequences should include the two maximum length sequences as well.  See JPL's website.</comment>
      <model>wikitext</model>
      <format>text/x-wiki</format>
      <text bytes="3562" xml:space="preserve">{{About|binary codes used in telecommunications ([[CDMA]]) and [[GPS]]|the authentication codes used to command a launch of nuclear weapons|Gold Codes}}
A '''Gold code''', also known as '''Gold sequence''', is a type of binary [[sequence]], used in [[telecommunication]] ([[CDMA]])&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|last1=George |first1=M. |last2=Hamid |first2=M. |last3=Miller |first3=A. |title=Gold Code Generators in Virtex Devices |publisher=Xilinx.com |url=http://www.xilinx.com/support/documentation/application_notes/xapp217.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080705134550/http://www.xilinx.com/support/documentation/application_notes/xapp217.pdf |archivedate=July 5, 2008 }}&lt;/ref&gt; and satellite navigation ([[GPS]]).&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |title=Transmitted GPS Signals |work=The GPS System |publisher=kowoma.de |url=http://www.kowoma.de/en/gps/signals.htm|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120804185510/http://www.kowoma.de/en/gps/signals.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-08-04}}&lt;/ref&gt; Gold codes are named after Robert Gold.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |title=Robert Gold, BS, MS, Ph.D. |date=2011 |publisher=Robert Gold Comm Systems|url=http://www.rgcsystems.com/ppl1_gold.htm}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |author=Gold, R. |title=Optimal binary sequences for spread spectrum multiplexing (Corresp.) |journal=IEEE Transactions on Information Theory |volume=13 |issue=4 |pages=619–621 |date=October 1967 |doi=10.1109/TIT.1967.1054048 }}&lt;/ref&gt; Gold codes have bounded small [[cross-correlation]]s within a set, which is useful when multiple devices are broadcasting in the same frequency range.  A set of Gold code sequences consists of 2&lt;sup&gt;''n''&lt;/sup&gt; + 1 sequences each one with a period of 2&lt;sup&gt;''n''&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;minus; 1.

A set of Gold codes can be generated with the following steps.  Pick two [[maximum length sequence]]s of the same length 2&lt;sup&gt;''n''&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;minus; 1 such that their absolute [[cross-correlation]] is less than or equal to 2&lt;sup&gt;(''n''+2)/2&lt;/sup&gt;, where ''n'' is the size of the [[linear feedback shift register]] used to generate the maximum length sequence (Gold '67).  The set of the 2&lt;sup&gt;''n''&lt;/sup&gt; &amp;minus; 1 [[exclusive-or]]s of the two sequences in their various phases (i.e. translated into all relative positions) together with the two maximum length sequences form a set of 2&lt;sup&gt;''n''&lt;/sup&gt; + 1  Gold code sequences.  The highest absolute cross-correlation in this set of codes is 2&lt;sup&gt;(''n''+2)/2&lt;/sup&gt; + 1 for even ''n'' and 2&lt;sup&gt;(''n''+1)/2&lt;/sup&gt; + 1 for odd ''n''.

The [[exclusive or]] of two different Gold codes from the same set is another Gold code in some phase.

Within a set of Gold codes about half of the codes are balanced{{spaced ndash}}the number of ones and zeros differs by only one.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|Holmes|2007|p=100}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Gold codes are used in [[GPS]]. The [[GPS signals#Coarse/acquisition code|GPS C/A]] ranging codes are Gold codes of period 1,023.

==See also==
*[[Kasami code]]
*[[Hadamard code]]
*[[Zadoff–Chu sequence]]
*[[Complementary sequences]]
*[[Space Network]] – a NASA system that uses Gold codes

